column1: 803116^The Weakness^https://images.genius.com/b408ba3b10beb1619ce589b2e7e08dad.600x603x1.png^2007-11-24^Abandoned in the plains. i have fought my way. through the winter of my sadness. through the desert of my anger. and bereft. circumvention is mine. for a father's hand is weak. and his love is futile. i have ground my affection in gnashed teeth. and cast away a lifetime of lies. there's deception in my blood. and in the end you will drown in it. the loss of your first born son. not to death. but the things that you have done. i am the bastard child of a broken heart. and bereavement is all i call my own. forsaken by my blood. i have vanquished armies of men alone. your guidance was currency. your compassion: criticism. your love: abandonment. blackened memory fading. the stains they shine beneath. your compassion. your concern for glamour. stakes great pain in me. a union of mandrake: silent. symptomatic. a cycle complete. repetition is your poison. one adulterous hand. one hand on scripture. the smile of a debtor is in your face. the tongue of a traitor beneath it. you recognize your fear and turn your back to it. you coward. in a moment of clarity. stillborn is the air. our shoulders have become your bier. because you are dead inside. your austere voice and morale. merely a facade for your cowardice. in a home where you play the master. in truth you are the mere apprentice

column10: say you scaredAndre begins after 1:38 of a lackluster rap song and performs a verse that simply flew over most listeners’ ears; it is the quintessential performance to demonstrate his stage stealing abilities.  The opening “paragraph indent” is an instant way to set the following lines up as something different than the preceding lines.  “I make intense sense” is a use of slang to inform the listener his verse will be exploring a topic with indisputable logic.  Andre grabs one’s attention and alerts him to look for an argument with this opening line
column11: which allows the line
column12: “Niggas on that Gill Scott dope (hint hint)
column13: ” to impart its intended meaning to the attentive listener.  The word “dope” in urban slang has traditionally primarily meant heroin – and subsequently caused this verse to be misunderstood by many. “Dope” is taking the place of the last name of “Gil Scott” which is Heron
column14: thus many attempted to combine the meaning of “dope” and its replacement of Heron to state the line meant “Niggas on that Heroin.”  This interpretation falls apart upon the most cursory inspection as it makes no sense in context. However
column15: “dope” also has two other common definitions in urban slang.  Those not familiar with slang often assume it means marijuana and subsequently use it to mean marijuana; while this meaning is still generally regarded as incorrect
column16: its prevalence warrants mention.  It is also used as an adjective meaning extremely cool or good (which is likely what lead to the incorrect use of the term to mean marijuana
column17: as referring one might refer to very good weed as being “dope”).Here Andre uses it to state that he and his friends believe Gill Scott Heron was cool. Gill Scott Heron is today known as the godfather of Hip-Hop and he infused his music with political messages that criticized Black Revolutionary hypocrisy
column18: pointed out white middle class America’s ignorance to the situation of inner-city communities
column19: urged the inner city to work to improve its condition and in his latest recordings directly addressed upcoming rap stars to plead with them to work for improvement of the life of others in the inner city instead of perpetuating or glorifying the lifestyle.  Outkast
column20: the duo of which Andre is one half
column21: often addressed these same issues and the “(hint hint)” informs the listener to keep Gill Scott Heron’s messages in mind.“At age fifteen they start smoking Billy Clint’” is an image of an inner city youth beginning to smoke marijuana (“Billy Clint’” meaning Bill Clinton
column22: who said: “When I was in England
column23: I experimented with marijuana a time or two
column24: and I didn’t like it. I didn’t inhale and never tried it again”).  Andre then jumps the age to twenty-one to illustrate that despite Gill Scott Heron’s admonitions those in the inner city are still not working to escape and improve the inner city.  The youth here entered High School at 15 where he may have escaped through academics or athletics (or other methods) but instead smoked weed and has found himself 21 and still caught in the inner city (“Hey hey hey what’s the haps? Well see your time elapsed”).  “Have you ever thought of the meaning of the word trapped” requires slang knowledge once again – the trap or trapping refers to both the inner city and the drug game; Andre is pointing out the inner city/drug game is an actual trap and now that our character has failed to escape in the 15 to 21 year old time period he now must depend on someone else to free him.  This issue troubles the 21 year old (“Baboon on your back” replacing the idiom monkey on your back
column25: which refers to having something constantly trouble one) but he is powerless.Andre then moves on to a new point of Gil Scott Heron’s but this time expands upon it.  Heron believed curing the middle class of their ignorance would incite a response and solution of the issues in the inner city.  Andre takes his audience beyond inner city blacks by including “Hispanic communities” when discussing the crack epidemic.  He specifically states “it got everyone’s undivided attention” after it “spread to white” however
column26: it is unlikely this is a race criticism as Andre never expresses racial statements in this way in other material.  It is more likely “white” simple works better than “middle-class.”  More important is the fact that the “crack” didn’t get “undivided attention” until it reached outside of inner city communities
column27: as this illustrates the middle class is still ignorant about the inner city.Andre expands upon Heron’s points here as well by noting the middle class did not know how to respond to the epidemic and was simply “scared to talk about it.”  Andre changes the song’s refrain’s meaning by starting this repetition of “scared” early.  When the listener reaches “if you scared
column29: ” it becomes an admonition to acknowledge problems.  Andre expands Heron’s message to every race
column30: illustrates the continuing problem
column31: and then points out and corrects the message’s error.  It is not merely enough to be aware of a problem – one must actually acknowledge and discuss the problem.  Being scared of the crack epidemic solves nothing
column33: say you scared.” Only then can the problems be solved.  In thirty-eight seconds
column34: Andre takes a simple rap song and packs in a fully realized political message.

column1: 523349^Congregation Kadimah Toras-Moshe v. Deleo^https://images.genius.com/e4ad2904dd08a0c00b5f4576a3e3437d.500x500x1.jpg^1989-06-11^Citation:405 Mass. 365 (Mass. 1989)LIACOS
column2: C.J.Congregation Kadimah Toras-Moshe (Congregation)
column3: an Orthodox Jewish synagogue
column4: commenced this action in the Superior Court to compel the administrator of an estate (estate) to fulfil the oral promise of the decedent to give the Congregation $25
column5: 000. The Superior Court transferred the case to the Boston Municipal Court
column6: which rendered summary judgement for the estate. The case was then transferred back to the Superior Court
column7: which also rendered summary judgement for the estate and dismissed the Congregation's complaint. We granted the Congregation's application for direct appellate review. We now affirm.The facts are not contested. The decedent suffered a prolonged illness
column8: throughout which he was visited by the Congregation's spiritual leader
column9: Rabbi Abraham Halbfinger. During four or five of these visits
column10: and in the presence of witnesses
column11: the decedent made an oral promise to give the Congregation $25
column12: 000. The Congregation planned to use the $25
column13: 000 to transform a storage room in the synagogue into a library named after the decedent. The oral promise was never reduced to writing. The decedent died intestate in September
column14: 1985. He had no children
column15: but was survived by his wife.The Congregation asserts that the decedent's oral promise is an enforceable contract under our case law
column16: because the promise is allegedly supported either by consideration and bargain
column17: or by reliance. See Loranger Constr. Corp. v. E.F. Hauserman Co.
column20: 763 (1978) (distinguishing consideration and bargain from reliance in the absence of consideration). We disagree.The Superior Court judge determined that [t]his was an oral gratuitous pledge
column21: with no indication as to how the money should be used
column22: or what [the Congregation] was required to do if anything in return for this promise. There was no legal benefit to the promisor nor detriment to the promisee
column23: and thus no consideration. See Marine Contractors Co. v. Hurley
column27: 186 (1972) (moral obligation is not legal obligation). Furthermore
column28: there is no evidence in the record that the Congregation's plans to name a library after the decedent induced him to make or to renew his promise. Contrast Allegheny College v. National Chautauqua County Bank
column30: 377-379 (1927) (subscriber's promise became binding when charity implicitly promised to commemorate subscriber).As to the lack of reliance
column31: the judge stated that the Congregation's allocation of $25
column33: ] for the purpose of renovating a storage room
column34: is insufficient to find reliance or an enforceable obligation. We agree. The inclusion of the promised $25
column37: merely reduced to writing the Congregation's expectation that it would have additional funds. A hope or expectation
column39: is not equivalent to either legal detriment or reliance.[2] Hall v. Horton House Microwave
column41: 24 Mass. App. Ct. 84
column42: 94 (1987).The Congregation cites several of our cases in which charitable subscriptions were enforced. These cases are distinguishable because they involved written
column44: promises and also involved substantial consideration or reliance. See
column46: Trustees of Amherst Academy v. Cowls
column47: 6 Pick. 427
column48: 434 (1828) (subscribers to written agreement could not withdraw after the execution or during the progress of the work which they themselves set in motion); Trustees of Farmington Academy v. Allen
column51: on the faith of the defendant's subscription). Conversely
column52: in the case of Cottage St. Methodist Episcopal Church v. Kendall
column54: we refused to enforce a promise in favour of a charity where there was no showing of any consideration or reliance.The Congregation asks us to abandon the requirement of consideration or reliance in the case of charitable subscriptions. The Congregation cites the Restatement (Second) of Contracts § 90 (1981)
column56: in subsection (2): A charitable subscription ... is binding under Subsection (1) without proof that the promise induced action or forbearance. Subsection (1)
column57: as modified in pertinent part by subsection (2)
column58: provides: A promise which the promiser should reasonably expect to induce action or forbearance on the part of the promisee or a third person ... is binding if injustice can be avoided only by enforcement of the promise....Assuming without deciding that this court would apply § 90
column59: we are of the opinion that in this case there is no injustice in declining to enforce the decedent's promise. Although § 90 dispenses with the absolute requirement of consideration or reliance
column60: the official comments illustrate that these are relevant considerations. Restatement (Second) of Contracts
column61: supra at § 90 comment f. The promise to the Congregation is entirely unsupported by consideration or reliance. Furthermore
column62: it is an oral promise sought to be enforced against an estate. To enforce such a promise would be against public policy.Judgement affirmed.Footnotes:[1] Of the estate of Saul Schwam.[2] We do not use the expression `promissory estoppel
column63: since it tends to confusion rather than clarify. Loranger Constr. Corp. v. E.F. Hauserman Co.
column65: 761 (1978).[3] The Congregation cites two cases for the proposition that Massachusetts requires so little consideration or reliance that
column67: none is required. The Congregation misconstrues each case.The Congregation interprets this court's opinion in Robinson v. Nutt

column1: 754064^Last Requiem For The Storm^https://assets.genius.com/images/default_cover_image.png?1668632954^^Descend into the abysmal depths; Wasting away in the trenches of existence. A cold darkness has fallen; The agony's welled up inside; The dams of vigor are breaking the; Torrent of anguish will no longer subside. Whilst night falls so comes the tide. As the rushing waves of pain crash; And the swirling waters of depression engulf you; As you lay gasping for air the illness festers within; Until surrender is the only option. Forever sorrow comes tonight as you decide to end your life. We shall meet again one day; at the two points of the circle; Where birth and death; are one and the same. As this world could not appease; Your desires or quell your miseries; You must venture out past its bounds; So take one last breath as you drown. This end shalt cause more suffering; But such is our task; We must persevere to traverse these dark waters; Lest we forget the tragedy. Time must heal all wounds; Time could not heal your wounds. A weakened soul incarcerated from within; A living hell that none should have to endure; In a world full of wondrous questions we ask why; At the end of this journey may we finally know. Words will never be able to convey; The emotions your actions have borne in me. For every tomorrow brings a new day of sorrow. Our mourning and bereavement; Succumbs to the dusk of acceptance. Days will pass on and so must we too; All sacrifice and all suffering is redemptive

column1: 521079^Ending a Sentence with a Preposition^https://images.genius.com/6fa3a1ec94553917f463b6f6a13b3ac2.400x400x1.jpg^2011-02-23^Welcome to Ask the Editor. I'm Emily Brewster
column2: an Associate Editor at Merriam-Webster.To some of you
column3: what I'm about to say will be a huge relief
column4: and to others—a complete abomination. Here it goes: A preposition is a perfectly appropriate kind of word to end a sentence with. So where did the rule telling us it's not okay to end a sentence with a preposition come from?Well
column5: it seems that the 17th-century English poet
column6: playwright and essayist John Dryden is to blame. In a 1672 essay
column7: Dryden castigated the writers of the generation preceding him
column8: a generation that included Shakespeare and Ben Jonson
column9: for a variety of things—among them ending sentences with prepositions.Dryden most likely objected to the terminal preposition because Latin doesn't allow the construction
column10: and it was fashionable at the time to assert that English should be more like Latin. Whatever the rationale behind it
column11: Dryden's objection got passed down as grammar law and written into the books used to teach grammar in schools.But really
column12: —you might ask—wasn't Dryden on to something? Don't sentences ending in prepositions sound sloppier than those that don't? Well
column13: maybe in some cases
column14: although that may be because we've been conditioned to think so. The fact is
column15: we've been using the terminal preposition since the days of Old English. And in some instances
column16: avoiding the terminal preposition makes things plain weird. Do we really want to change a sentence like Give them what they asked for to Give them the thing for which they asked?So I say
column17: when it feels natural to end a sentence in a preposition
column18: do so. And if someone gives you a hard time about it
column19: feel free to respond to the criticism as Winston Churchill according to unconfirmed legend did
column20: his tongue firmly in cheek: This is just the sort of nonsense up with which I will not put.Tune in again soon for future installments of Ask the Editor here at merriam-webster.com.

column13: I found that the people I had the most rapport with were the babies. And one of the things I noticed about these babies was that they were apparently being used as some kind of traffic testers. Their mothers would be pushing them along in their strollers--and they would come to a busy street with lots of parked cars--and the mother can't see what the traffic is like because of all the parked cars--so she just sort of edges the stroller out into the street and cranes her head out afterwards. And the most striking thing about this is the expression on these babies' faces as they sit there in the middle of traffic
